fields.description:
*Assessment*

When launching an EBS-backed EMI in Eucalyptus, the following is seen for block device mapping:
{code}
ubuntu@euca-172-17-126-171:~$ curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/block-device-mapping/
ami
ebs1
emi
ephemeral0
{code}
All the block devices here are correct except _ebs1_.  (This EBS-backed EMI was registered with the block device mapping option of _"/dev/sdc=ephemeral0"_, therefore ephemeral shows up). This is different than what is seen on AWS, where you have an EBS-backed AMI registered the same way:
{code}
ubuntu@domU-12-31-39-05-28-55:~$ curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/block-device-mapping/
ami
ephemeral0
root
swap
{code}

*Steps*

* Set up Eucalyptus 3.4.1 cloud
* Download and source admin creds of eucalyptus account
* Download tar-gzipped precise-server-cloudimg:
{code}
$ wget http://cloud-images.ubuntu.com/precise/current/precise-server-cloudimg-amd64.tar.gz
{code}
* Create an instance stored-backed EMI using eustore:
{code}
$ eustore-install-image -t precise-server-cloudimg-amd64.tar.gz -b ubuntu-latest-precise-x86_64 --hypervisor universal -s "Ubuntu Cloud Image - Precise Pangolin - 12.04 LTS"
{code}
* Run instance using that EMI (for example):
{code}
$ euca-run-instances -t m1.medium -k account1-user01 emi-5C8C3909
{code}
* Create a volume based upon the size of how big you want the root filesystem to be (for example):
{code}
$ euca-create-volume -s 6 -z LayinDaSmackDown
{code}
* Attach the volume to the running instance (for example):
{code}
$ euca-attach-volume -d /dev/vdd -i i-839E3FB0 vol-B5863B3
{code}
SSH into the instance and download the Ubuntu Precise Cloud Image (qcow2 format) - for example:
{code}
$ ssh -i account1-user01.priv ubuntu@euca-10-104-7-10.eucalyptus.euca-hasp.eucalyptus-systems.com
# sudo -s
# wget http://cloud-images.ubuntu.com/precise/current/precise-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.img
{code}
* Install qemu-utils
{code}
# apt-get install -y qemu-utils
{code}
* Convert image from qcow2 to raw:
{code}
# qemu-img convert -O raw precise-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1.img precise-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1-raw.img
{code}
* dd raw image to block device where volume is attached (use dmesg to figure that out easily):
{code}
# dmesg | tail
[ 7026.943212] virtio-pci 0000:00:05.0: using default PCI settings
[ 7026.943249] pci 0000:00:07.0: no hotplug settings from platform
[ 7026.943251] pci 0000:00:07.0: using default PCI settings
[ 7026.945964] virtio-pci 0000:00:07.0: enabling device (0000 -> 0003)
[ 7026.955143] virtio-pci 0000:00:07.0: PCI INT A -> Link[LNKC] -> GSI 10 (level, high) -> IRQ 10
[ 7026.955180] virtio-pci 0000:00:07.0: setting latency timer to 64
[ 7026.955429] virtio-pci 0000:00:07.0: irq 45 for MSI/MSI-X
[ 7026.955456] virtio-pci 0000:00:07.0: irq 46 for MSI/MSI-X
[ 7026.986990]  vdb: unknown partition table
[10447.093426] virtio-pci 0000:00:07.0: PCI INT A disabled

# dd if=/mnt/precise-server-cloudimg-amd64-disk1-raw.img of=/dev/vdb bs=1M
{code}
* Log out the instance, and detach the volume (for example):
{code}
$ euca-detach-volume vol-B5863B3B
{code}
*  Create a snapshot of the volume (for example):
{code}
$ euca-create-snapshot vol-B5863B3B
{code}
* Register the snapshot to create the EBS-backed EMI:
{code}
$ euca-register --name EBS-Precise-RAW-ephemeral --snapshot snap-EFDB40A1 --root-device-name /dev/sda -b "/dev/sdc=ephemeral0" --region account1-user01@
IMAGE	emi-E2DF4533
{code}
* Run instance:
{code}
$ euca-run-instances -k account1-user01 -t m1.medium emi-E2DF4533 --region account1-user01@
RESERVATION	r-41AF424A	961915002812	default
INSTANCE	i-42DC3F56	emi-E2DF4533	euca-0-0-0-0.eucalyptus.euca-hasp.eucalyptus-systems.com	euca-0-0-0-0.eucalyptus.internal	pending	account1-user01	0		m1.medium	2014-01-29T19:42:24.003Z	LayinDaSmackDown				monitoring-disabled	0.0.0.0	0.0.0.0			ebs					hvm

$ euca-describe-instances i-42DC3F56 --region account1-user01@
RESERVATION	r-41AF424A	961915002812	default
INSTANCE	i-42DC3F56	emi-E2DF4533	euca-10-104-7-13.eucalyptus.euca-hasp.eucalyptus-systems.com	euca-172-17-126-171.eucalyptus.internal	running	account1-user01	0		m1.medium	2014-01-29T19:42:24.003Z	LayinDaSmackDown				monitoring-disabled	10.104.7.13	172.17.126.171			ebs					hvm
BLOCKDEVICE	/dev/sda	vol-781E3E7D	2014-01-29T19:42:24.286Z	true
{code}
* SSH into instance, get metadata service:
{code}
$ ssh -i account1-user01.priv ubuntu@euca-10-104-7-13.eucalyptus.euca-hasp.eucalyptus-systems.com
ubuntu@euca-172-17-126-171:~$ curl http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/block-device-mapping/
ami
ebs1
emi
ephemeral0
{code}

*Pertinent Data*

As displayed in the _Assessment_ area, this is a different behavior than AWS.  _ebs1_ is not part of the [AWS instance metadata categories|http://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSEC2/latest/UserGuide/AESDG-chapter-instancedata.html#instancedata-data-categories] when not mapping EBS volumes as part of block device mapping option.
